                        <h3 class="mb-4">About Opals</h3>
                        
                        <div class="accordion" id="accordionOpals">
                            <div class="accordion-item mb-3">
                                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingOne">
                                    <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseOne" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseOne">
                                        What makes opals unique among gemstones?
                                    </button>
                                </h2>
                                <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingOne" data-bs-parent="#accordionOpals">
                                    <div class="accordion-body">
                                        <p>Opals are unique among gemstones because of their ability to diffract light, creating a phenomenon known as "play-of-color." This occurs due to the microscopic silica spheres within the stone that break up light into the colors of the spectrum. No two opals are exactly alike, making each one a truly one-of-a-kind gemstone.</p>
                                        <p>Additionally, opals contain water (typically 5-10%), which contributes to their unique optical properties but also requires special care compared to other gemstones.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            
                            <div class="accordion-item mb-3">
                                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwo">
                                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo">
                                        What are the different types of opals?
                                    </button>
                                </h2>
                                <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwo" data-bs-parent="#accordionOpals">
                                    <div class="accordion-body">
                                        <p>There are several types of opals, each with unique characteristics:</p>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li><strong>Black Opals:</strong> The most valuable type, with a dark body tone that enhances the play-of-color.</li>
                                            <li><strong>White/Milk Opals:</strong> Have a light body tone, often with vibrant play-of-color.</li>
                                            <li><strong>Boulder Opals:</strong> Form in ironstone boulders, often with the host rock left as a backing.</li>
                                            <li><strong>Fire Opals:</strong> Transparent to translucent with a warm body color (yellow, orange, red).</li>
                                            <li><strong>Crystal Opals:</strong> Transparent to semi-transparent with a clear background.</li>
                                            <li><strong>Matrix Opals:</strong> Opal material that forms within the cracks of the host rock.</li>
                                        </ul>
                                        <p>Additionally, opals can be categorized by their structure:</p>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li><strong>Solid Opals:</strong> Natural, solid pieces of opal.</li>
                                            <li><strong>Doublets:</strong> A thin layer of opal cemented to a backing material.</li>
                                            <li><strong>Triplets:</strong> A thin layer of opal with a backing and a clear protective cap on top.</li>
                                        </ul>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            
                            <div class="accordion-item mb-3">
                                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
                                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
                                        Where do opals come from?
                                    </button>
                                </h2>
                                <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree" data-bs-parent="#accordionOpals">
                                    <div class="accordion-body">
                                        <p>Australia is the world's primary source of high-quality opals, producing approximately 95% of the world's precious opals. The major Australian opal fields include:</p>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li><strong>Lightning Ridge (New South Wales):</strong> Famous for black opals</li>
                                            <li><strong>Coober Pedy (South Australia):</strong> Known for white opals</li>
                                            <li><strong>Andamooka (South Australia):</strong> Produces crystal and matrix opals</li>
                                            <li><strong>Queensland:</strong> Source of boulder opals</li>
                                        </ul>
                                        <p>Other countries that produce opals include:</p>
                                        <ul>
                                            <li><strong>Ethiopia:</strong> Recently discovered deposits producing high-quality opals</li>
                                            <li><strong>Mexico:</strong> Known for fire opals</li>
                                            <li><strong>Brazil:</strong> Produces various types of opals</li>
                                            <li><strong>United States:</strong> Nevada, Idaho, and Oregon have opal deposits</li>
                                        </ul>
                                        <p>At Ottawa Opal Shop, we primarily source our opals from Australian mines, ensuring the highest quality and ethical sourcing practices.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            
                            <div class="accordion-item mb-3">
                                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFour">
                                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFour" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFour">
                                        Are opals considered birthstones?
                                    </button>
                                </h2>
                                <div id="collapseFour" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFour" data-bs-parent="#accordionOpals">
                                    <div class="accordion-body">
                                        <p>Yes, opal is the traditional birthstone for October. It shares this distinction with tourmaline, which is the modern October birthstone.</p>
                                        <p>Opals are also associated with the 14th wedding anniversary, making them a meaningful gift for couples celebrating this milestone.</p>
                                        <p>Throughout history, opals have been associated with good luck, creativity, passion, and spontaneity. They were highly prized by ancient Romans, who believed they combined the powers of all gemstones due to their multi-colored appearance.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
